		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=609"><span id=>Lasae</span></a><b><span id=></span></b><br>3 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.67]</nobr><br><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Lasae&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>I play a Wood Elven Warrior on Vallon Zek, Lasae Leniyersa, level 54 so I'd like to clarify a few issues here:<br><br>"2) High Intelligence, especially relative to the Large races. This means skills max out quickly. It's a rare day that my combat skills don't all max out before I've reached the 3rd bubble of XP for a given level. How many Ogre Warriors can say the same?"<br><br>75 Int based on a Wood Elf Warrior...Gnomes and Dark Elves have higher base int.<br><br>"4) Don't underestimate the usefulness of the Forage skill. Keep at it and it will pay off big and it will pay off soon. I bought 20 each of milk and bread to hold me over, and then hotkeyed Forage in a place where I could keep an eye on it. When I wasn't in combat, I'd hit that key religiously, like it was Sense Heading. By the time I had run out of bread and milk, I my backpack was brimming with water and gathered food. It's been about 5 levels since I spent any money on food. Now I only Forage every other level - otherwise, I'd have more food and water than I could carry."<br><br>Correction: Foraging is *worthless* you will find that 2 out of every 5 successful forages is a fishing grub, 1 out 5 is water, and the rest either berries, fruit, or veggies.&nbsp;&nbsp;The problem is that it will take up 4 slots in your backpack and you will almost always run out of water because you only forage it 20% of the time you are successful.  Wood Elf warriors have their foraging capped at 20 skill, so you successfully forage *something* maybe 33% of the time.  So you have a 6% or so chance of foraging water, maybe even less.<br><br>"5) Nor should you dismiss the tactical value of the Hide skill - though, as with Forage, you have to use it correctly to reap the full benefit. You will no doubt experience downtime while healing the likes of which you can't yet imagine. Sit down within sight, but not within aggro range, of a monster that doesn't /con indifferent to you. Then hide. Then target that monster and /con him until you get an indifferent result. It's the only way to be sure that your hide check succeeded. I can't tell you how many times I've sat at the Crushbone Entrance licking my wounds in concealment inches away from a train of Emporer Crush and his Legionnaires. Or how many times one of those trains squashed me like a bug because I forgot to make sure that my Hide check succeeded before I let my guard down."<br><br>The above I agree with 100%, great for PvP too. <br><br>Finally, for small races, it is ABSOLUTELY critical to learn how to Shield Bash.<br><br>Quoted from the Warrior FAQ on Stratics:<br><br>"By all means yes, bashing a monster to interrupt spellcasting or stun it is very valuable.  Large races can slam, but small races should use the ghetto/Ruatha bash method.  To do this, set up a hotkey bank with your secondary melee slot and one of your inventory slots, next to each other or one on top of the other, along with the Bash button.  Put your shield in the inventory slot and go into combat while dual wielding.  Click on the shield to pick it up and move the cursor over the secondary melee slot, and leave it there.  When bash is ready, click the mouse to switch items, press bash (using the number keys, not the mouse), then click to switch back.  Practice with a cheap weapon and shield in case you drop them, until you feel confident that you won't drop your items.  It is also possible to bash while using a two-handed weapon, but to do this you would need to click on the weapon, then click on the shield inventory slot (to swap them), then click on the secondary melee slot, bash, and switch it all back."<br><br><a href="http://eq.stratics.com/content/classes/warrior/classes_warrior_faq.shtml#3.4" target=_new>http://eq.stratics.com/content/classes/warrior/classes_warrior_faq.shtml#3.4</a></p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >2 Replies</td></tr></table><table width="100%"><tr><td class=mhback>&nbsp;</td><td class=mhback >Thread Subject</a></td><td class=mhback>Started by</a></td><td class=mhback>Replies</a></td><td class=mhback>Last Post</a></td><td class=mhback>Rating</a></td></tr><tr class=mlr>
